Anonymous Sun 28 Aug 2022 19:44:01 No.50509798 Report
Quoted By: >>50509843 >>50509920 >>50509988
>>50509383
>why exactly did you leave JP?
>or was it a temporary thing from the start?
Started out as a temporary gig teaching English, but honestly speaking almost turned permanent with how much I loved it
I worked out in the middle of podunk nowhere and the cost of living was so low I had a TON of money to mess around with despite being paid the equivalent of $13 an hour
If I told you how much my rent was for a pet-friendly two-bedroom apartment you'd probably weep
As for why I left, there were three big reasons:

1: The longer you live there as a foreigner, the higher your tax becomes, and after five years it got to the point where I had to choose to stay there forever or move back to the US
2: Staying would effectively mean abandoning my entire family and unfortunately I do actually love them
3: The Japanese pension system is really weird in that, if you want to access your pension, you can only do so either within the first five years of you paying into it OR after age 60, and I REALLY didn't want to leave over $10,000 on the table by staying another year

For anyone just getting out of college who wants to pay off their loans really quickly while ALSO getting to see Japan, I highly recommend signing up for an Assistant Language Teacher (ALT) job through either the JET Program or a private company like Interac.

Anonymous Mon 29 Aug 2022 00:14:01 No.50516645 Report
Quoted By: >>50516743
>>50516229
I'm an edit-up person myself, so a word of caution. Don't confuse context with worldbuilding for the sole sake of worldbuilding. Let the reader infer through pacing and what isn't said, as well as through what you choose to show and what is told.
You can establish a conflict and setting in very few words, even a complex one.
In my story, the reader spends several chapters in a certain setting. But everything that is shown comes together with under 500 words of an internal story (context) and a fight resolution (which shows the perception of said story)
Showing that core conflict in a more expanded, show-y way that interrupted the plot? Maybe 10k words. The pacing didn't demand that.

Your characters are the context. Make them breathe and the readers will get it.

You sound like you have the same issue I had.

More or less.
Take some relatively famous works. Arthur of Le Morte D'Arthur may be human, but his society would be based around a life experience that produces a different thought process. His philosophy of life wouldn't match ours.
